<p>Whether you=E2=80=99re a seasoned baker or simply want to learn more abo=
ut cooking, it=E2=80=99s important to know the basic conversions for dry me=
asurements. This is especially crucial if you find that your one tablespoon=
 is in the dishwasher!</p>
<p><strong>So how many teaspoons in a tablespoon? How many tablespoons in a=
 cup?</strong> We answer all these questions and more in this guide to conv=
ersions for imperial dry measurements. We also give you a couple of tips fo=
r memorizing these need-to-know conversions.</p>
<p><!--more--></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2>How Many Teaspoons in a Tablespoon?</h2><ins class=3D"adsbygoogle width=
-responsive" data-ad-client=3D"ca-pub-1230785017580231" data-ad-slot=3D"261=
6086100" style=3D"margin: 0px 0px 2em; width: 500px; height: 90px;" data-ad=
sbygoogle-status=3D"done"><div id=3D"aswift_1_host" style=3D"border: none; =
height: 90px; width: 500px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; position: relative; =
visibility: visible; background-color: transparent; display: inline-block;"=
></div></ins>
<p><strong>There are 3 teaspoons (tsp) in 1 tablespoon (tbsp, Tbsp, or T).<=
/strong></p>
<p>So if you didn=E2=80=99t have a tablespoon on hand and had a recipe that=
 called for 1 tablespoon of some ingredient, you could <strong>use a teaspo=
on<em> three times</em> to get that same amount</strong>.</p>
<p>Here=E2=80=99s a quick teaspoon to tablespoon conversion chart you can u=
se as a reference:</p>
<table border=3D"1px" cellpadding=3D"5px" style=3D"border-collapse: collaps=
e;">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>
<p><strong>Tablespoon (tbsp)</strong></p>
</td>
<td>
<p><strong>Teaspoon (tsp)</strong></p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
<p>4 tbsp</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>12 tsp</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
<p>3 tbsp</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>9 tsp</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
<p>2 tbsp</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>6 tsp</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
<p>1 tbsp</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>3 tsp</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
<p>1/2 tbsp</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>1 1/2 tsp</p>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The pattern here is <strong>simply multiplying the number of tablespoons=
 you=E2=80=99ll need by 3 to get the equivalent number of teaspoons</strong=
>. So if a recipe calls for 3 tbsp of butter, for example, you could substi=
tute that with 9 tsp of butter (because 3 * 3 =3D 9).</p>
<p>If, on the other hand, you need to convert tsp to tbsp, you would <stron=
g>do the opposite and divide the number of tsp by 3</strong>. Instead of 6 =
tsp of cinnamon, for instance, you could use 2 tbsp (because 6 <span>=C3=B7=
</span> 3 =3D 2).</p>
<p>So how many tsp in a tbsp? 3. This also means that 1 tsp =3D 1/3 tbsp.</=
p>
<p><strong>Now, what if you need to convert tsp to cups? Or cups to tbsp?</=
strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><img alt=3D"body_measuring_cups" src=3D"ht=
tps://360031.fs1.hubspotusercontent-na1.net/hub/360031/hubfs/body_measuring=
_cups.jpg?width=3D456&amp;name=3Dbody_measuring_cups.jpg" style=3D"width: 4=
56px; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" width=3D"456"=
><span style=3D"font-size: 10px;"><em><a href=3D"https://www.flickr.com/pho=
tos/joeyz51/33915157778/in/photolist-TEY3PC-4UcFTL-Nk5ah-85Dejo-26qP7k3-bca=
Ktt-71bqLU-5XZiKs-QtjgPY-23QDdPA-anNMnT-4h1HL4-aSVgvR-bbBnXr-2d5kqu3-bE5qEq=
-6Bq827-6gW9Gy-anNN44-4X15Aq-5Ux6pa-9neeM-6CaeMG-9F7Psj-9qrbK8-anRzi7-pLph5=
