 none; height: 90px; width: 500px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; position: rel=
ative; visibility: visible; background-color: transparent; display: inline-=
block;"></div></ins>
<p>Many recipes that call for dry ingredients, such as flour, sugar, baking=
 powder, or specific spices, will require you to use not only teaspoons and=
 tablespoons but also cups, which are even bigger than tablespoons.</p>
<p>But what if you don=E2=80=99t have any cups? Or you need to cut a recipe=
 in half and end up with strange measurements you don=E2=80=99t have measur=
ing cups for, such as 1/6 cup or 3/8 cup?</p>
<p>This is why it=E2=80=99s helpful to know what the conversions are betwee=
n tsp, tbsp, and cups. You already know there are 3 tsp in a tbsp, so what =
about cups? <strong>There are 16 tbsp in 1 cup; this means that there are 4=
8 tsp in 1 cup.</strong></p>
<p>The following chart shows all the major imperial dry measurement convers=
ions you should know:</p>
<table border=3D"1px" cellpadding=3D"5px" style=3D"border-collapse: collaps=
e;">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>
<p><strong>Cup (c)</strong></p>
</td>
<td>
<p><strong>Tablespoon (tbsp)</strong></p>
</td>
<td>
<p><strong>Teaspoon (tsp)</strong></p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
<p>1 c</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>16 tbsp</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>48 tsp</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
<p>3/4 c</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>12 tbsp</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>36 tsp</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
<p>2/3 c</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>10 tbsp + 2 tsp</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>32 tsp</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
<p>1/2 c</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>8 tbsp</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>24 tsp</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
<p>3/8 c</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>6 tbsp</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>18 tsp</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
<p>1/3 c</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>5 tbsp + 1 tsp</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>16 tsp</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
<p>1/4 c</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>4 tbsp</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>12 tsp</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
<p>1/6 c</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>2 tbsp + 2 tsp</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>8 tsp</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
<p>1/8 c</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>2 tbsp</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>6 tsp</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
<p>1/16 c</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>1 tbsp</p>
</td>
<td>
<p>3 tsp</p>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Here=E2=80=99s a free PDF version of these measurement conversio=
n charts</strong> so you can keep them for future reference (we suggest han=
ging it up in your kitchen). Simply click the image to download it:</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://360031.fs1.hubspotusercontent-na1.net/hubfs/360031/Im=
perial%20Dry%20Measurements%20Conversion%20Charts.pdf" rel=3D"noopener"><im=
g alt=3D"body_imperial_dry_measurements_conversion_charts_thumbnail" src=3D=
"https://360031.fs1.hubspotusercontent-na1.net/hub/360031/hubfs/body_imperi=
al_dry_measurements_conversion_charts_thumbnail.png?width=3D220&amp;name=3D=
body_imperial_dry_measurements_conversion_charts_thumbnail.png" style=3D"wi=
dth: 220px; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" width=
=3D"220"></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2>2 Tips for Remembering Dry Measurement Conversions</h2>
<p>To wrap up, here are two useful tips to help you better remember these c=
onversions.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h3>#1: For Tablespoons to Teaspoons, Multiply by 3</h3>
<p>As we discussed above, 1 tbsp =3D 3 tsp. By this logic, 1 tsp =3D 1/3 tb=
sp.</p>
<p>If you need to convert tbsp to tsp, all you need to do is <strong>multip=
ly the number of tbsp needed by 3</strong>. Likewise, if you=E2=80=99re doi=
ng a teaspoon to tablespoon conversion, you would need to simply divide the=
 number of tsp by 3 to get its equivalent in tbsp.</p>
<p>Still having trouble remembering this? Try using <a href=3D"https://www.=
simplemost.com/how-many-ounces-pound-easy-conversion-tricks/" rel=3D"noopen=
er" target=3D"_blank">this catchy saying</a>:<strong> "One big T equals tea=
spoons three."</strong> (Remember that a tablespoon can be represented by a=
 capital T!)</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h3>#2: For Cups to Tablespoons, Multiply by 16</h3>
<p>Anytime you need to convert cups to tablespoons (or even to teaspoons), =
just recall that there are 16 tablespoons in 1 cup. Thus, to find out how m=
any tbsp you need, simply <strong>multiply the number of cups a recipe call=
s for by 16</strong>.</p>
<p>For example, say a recipe calls for 1 3/4 cups of sugar but you only hav=
e a tablespoon on hand. All you'd need to do is multiply 1 3/4 by 16 to get=
 its equivalent in tbsp:</p>
<div class=3D"example-blue">1 3/4 =3D 7/4<br>7/4 * 16/1 =3D 112/4<br>=3D <s=
trong>28 tbsp</strong></div>
<p>If you ever want to check your math, just use the chart above as a refer=
ence. In this case, you=E2=80=99d add together the number of tablespoons li=
sted for both "1 cup" and "3/4 cup." <strong>This gets you the same answer:=
 28 tbsp.</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2>What=E2=80=99s Next?</h2>
<p><strong>You now know how many tsp are in a tbsp and how many tbsp are in=
 a cup<span>=E2=80=94but what about how many cups are in a quart?</span> </=
strong>Check out <a href=3D"https://blog.prepscholar.com/how-many-cups-is-4=
-quarts-conversion" rel=3D"noopener" target=3D"_blank">our article on how t=
o convert cups to quarts</a>.</p>
<p><strong>What is the <a href=3D"https://blog.prepscholar.com/convert-cels=
ius-to-fahrenheit" rel=3D"noopener" target=3D"_blank">conversion between Fa=
hrenheit and Celsius</a>?</strong> Learn this easy and essential trick for =
converting from one unit of temperature to another.</p>
<p><strong>Maybe you're wondering <a href=3D"https://blog.prepscholar.com/c=
onvert-decimal-to-fraction" rel=3D"noopener" target=3D"_blank">how to conve=
rt fractions to decimals</a>. </strong>If so, you should definitely read ou=
r expert guide on it!</p></span>

